"""Easy to version control.
Jenkins can read it directly from your repo (“Pipeline from SCM”).
Anyone who clones the project can run the same CI pipeline.

Alternative: You can also paste the pipeline directly inside Jenkins (as “Pipeline script”), but keeping it in the repo is better.""

"""
Q2: How to “connect” pytest with Jenkins?
Jenkins doesn’t connect to pytest directly. Instead:
Jenkins pulls your code (from Git).
Jenkins runs a command like pytest ....
Jenkins collects artifacts (reports, screenshots).
So the connection is: Jenkins ↔ your repo.
Your pytest runs as a command inside Jenkins."""

"""
Step 3 Path A — You use Git (GitHub)
This is the recommended path.
Steps:
In PyCharm, initialize git and push your project to a remote (e.g., GitHub).
Add a Jenkinsfile at the root of your repo.
In Jenkins:

Create New Item → Pipeline
In “Pipeline” section:

Definition: Pipeline script from SCM
SCM: Git
Repository URL: your repo URL
Credentials: (if private)
Branch: main
Script Path: Jenkinsfile
Save → Build Now
Done. Jenkins will fetch your code and run pytest.
"""

